<section xml:id="section-assignment-week3">
  <title>Week 3 Assignment</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Write the first vector as a linear combination of the second
        and third vectors.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <me>
              \begin{pmatrix}
                4 \\ 3 
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                0 \\ 9 
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                3  \\ -5 
              \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \begin{pmatrix}
                0 \\ 4 \\ 11 
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                -1 \\ -2 \\ 1 
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                0 \\ 5 \\ -2 
              \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Write a third vector which is linearly independent to the
        first two. (Make sure you show me why is it linearly
        independent.)
        <ol>
          <li>
            <me>
              \begin{pmatrix}
                0 \\ -4 \\ -4  
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                3 \\ 0 \\ 0 
              \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \begin{pmatrix}
                1 \\ 1 \\ -4 
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                2 \\ -3 \\ 1 
              \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Write equations for these planes.
        <ol>
          <li>
            The plane with normal 
            <m>\begin{pmatrix}
              -7 \\ -1 \\ -1 
            \end{pmatrix}</m>
            containing the point
            <m>\begin{pmatrix}
              4 \\ 0 \\ 2 
            \end{pmatrix}</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The plane containing the points 
            <m>\begin{pmatrix}
              4 \\ 8 \\ 0 
            \end{pmatrix}, </m>
            <m>\begin{pmatrix}
              1 \\ -5 \\ -5 
            \end{pmatrix}</m> and 
            <m>\begin{pmatrix}
              -3 \\ 10 \\ 2 
            \end{pmatrix}</m>.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Prove that any three vectors in <m>\RR^2</m> must be linearly
        dependent. 
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
</section>
